It is the most common inherited disorder caused by a single gene and manifests in patients as mild symptoms such as café au lait macules and Lisch nodules, as well as more severe symptoms such as neurofibromas (tumor-like growths), skeletal abnormalities, malignant neoplasms, and learning disabilities. As technology continues to develop, it is now increasingly common to perform genetic analysis on patients to determine their NF1 mutational status. Since neurofibromin negatively regulates RAS proteins, these become more active in patient cells. datasets.name: Exploiting macropinocytosis for therapeutic delivery to Nf2-deficient schwannoma cells
datasets.description_clean: Exploiting macropinocytosis for therapeutic delivery to Nf2-deficient schwannoma cells Investigator: Jeremie Vitte Initiative: Drug Discovery Initiative Registered Reports (DDIRR) CTF Grant ID: Abstract: Significance/Rationale The benign, slow-growing nature of schwannomas presents unique challenges to therapeutic intervention, precluding the use of strategies that target rapidly dividing, metabolically active cells, and diminishing the therapeutic window for treatment. Recent work from the McClatchey lab, showed that merlin deficiency noticeably primes the membrane:cytoskeleton interface for growth factor-induced macropinocytosis, including in schwannoma cells. Mounting evidence suggests that beyond its physiological roles, macropinocytosis is also an important conduit for the delivery of therapeutic macromolecules into tumor cells. Since target cell entry is rate-limiting for many macro-therapeutics, tumor cells that are macropinocytosis-proficient may be particularly amenable to these promising strategies. Moreover, once internalized, macropinosomes merge with the endolysosomal system, and it is generally thought that slowing or impeding endolysosomal processing protects the contents from lysosomal degradation and enhances macro-therapeutic efficacy. The goal of this proposal is to evaluate the in vivo uptake of stapled peptides by Nf2-/- schwannoma cells via macropinocytosis. We will monitor the ability of Nf2-/- cells to internalize two fluorescently stapled peptides in vivo: one that mimics the BH3-domain of pro-apoptotic proteins to inhibit BCL2 family members and one that inhibits histone deacetylase (HDAC) family members. datasets.name: From cold to hot - Reprogramming tumor microenvironment to target NF1 malignancies
datasets.description_clean: From cold to hot - Reprogramming tumor microenvironment to target NF1 malignancies From cold to hot - Reprogramming tumor microenvironment to target NF1 malignancies CTF - Young Investigator Award Principal Investigator: Bandarigoda Nipunika Somatilaka Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Bandarigoda Nipunika Somatilaka Institution: University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center Project Description: Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) affects about 1 in 3000 people worldwide. Patients with NF1 often develop benign tumors on the skin and along the nerves in the spinal cord and brain, and about 8-13% of those become cancerous over time. These cancerous tumors are called Malignant Peripheral Nerve Sheath Tumors (MPNST). The only method of curing MPNST is surgical removal, however, these tumors can be large and located close to complex nerve networks, making complete removal difficult. As a result, tumors tend to reappear after surgery or tumor cells migrate to different sites like lung or bone. When complete removal cannot be achieved, radiotherapy and chemotherapy are recommended to manage the tumor. Unfortunately, MPNST respond poorly to both these therapies. With this lack of treatment options, survival of patients with MPNST is low. NF1 is caused by a mutation of the NF1 gene, which encodes a protein called neurofibromin. Neurofibromin acts as an off-switch for downstream signaling pathways. Therefore, inactivating mutations of the NF1 gene produce non-functional neurofibromin resulting in constant signaling of these pathways. Researchers have tried to target these pathways with various drugs to treat MPNST, however clinical trials testing these drugs against MPNST were not successful. Therefore, finding a druggable target for MPNST has been challenging. Given the difficulty of surgical and clinical management, identifying an effective treatment strategy for MPNST is a desperate need. A recent approach to treating inoperable, undruggable cancer has been to use Immune Check

datasets.name: Bromodomain Inhibitors to Prevent Development of Resistance to Targeted Kinase Inhibitors in Schwannomas
datasets.description_clean: Bromodomain Inhibitors to Prevent Development of Resistance to Targeted Kinase Inhibitors in Schwannomas Bromodomain Inhibitors to Prevent Development of Resistance to Targeted Kinase Inhibitors in Schwannomas Other - Investigator-Initiated Research Award Principal Investigator: Cristina Fernandez-Valle Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Cristina Fernandez-Valle, Haley Hardin Institution: University of Central Florida Project Description: Neurofibromatosis type 2 (NF2) is an inherited disorder that promotes tumor growth on nerves throughout the nervous system. NF2 affects around 1 in 33,000 individuals worldwide and is caused by loss of function of the merlin tumor suppressor encoded by the NF2 gene. Tumor control early in life is critical for maintaining quality of life. Currently, treatments available for NF2-associated tumors are surgery and radiation therapy. Off-label use of cancer drugs are being tried, as there are no Food and Drug Administration (FDA)-approved drug therapies for NF2. As a member of the SYNODOS for NF2 consortium, we performed unbiased drug combination screening using schwannoma model cell lines. We identified a BRD4 and a PAK inhibitor that acted in concert to selectively slow growth of a human schwannoma line compared to its merlin-expressing parental line. BRD4 is a member of the BET family of bromodomain containing proteins that bind acetylated lysine in transcription regulatory proteins to alter gene expression. BRD proteins contribute to development of resistance to cancer drugs. Follow-up studies confirmed the drugs’ interaction in multiple mouse and human schwannoma lines. We will extend this research by assessing the ability of BRD4 inhibitors in combination with multiple PAK, PI3K, MEK, and FAK inhibitors, some of which are in NF2 clinical trials (selumetinib, crizotinib, brigatinib, trametinib) to reduce the viability of schwannoma lines. We will measure whether the combinations provide long-lasting inhibition of cell proliferation,

datasets.description_clean: Assembloid Platform to Model Cellular Interactions Driving NF1 Glioma Assembloid Platform to Model Cellular Interactions Driving NF1 Glioma GFF - Next Generation Models Principal Investigator: Nereo Kalebic, Blagoje Soskic Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Nereo Kalebic, Blagoje Soskic Institution: Human Technopole Project Description: The Assembloid Platform to Model Cellular Interactions Driving NF1 Glioma project aims to create a sophisticated in vitro model system to study how different cell types interact and contribute to the development of brain tumors in neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1). By combining brain organoids with immune cells and using advanced genetic techniques, the researchers will create 'assembloids' that better represent the complex tumor environment. This approach will help understand how immune responses and cellular interactions influence tumor growth and potentially reveal new therapeutic strategies for NF1-associated brain tumors. For the past 25 years, the preclinical study of NF1 cognition in rodents has primarily utilized a single Nf1 mouse strain and a relatively small number of cognitive tests that do not have equivalent human tests. As this model has failed to predict the impact of therapeutics in NF1 individuals adequately, superior Nf1 rodent strains and cognitive tests, with equivalent human tests, are required. datasets.name: Self-updating causal models to accelerate discovery in NF
datasets.description_clean: Self-updating causal models to accelerate discovery in NF Self-updating causal models to accelerate discovery in Neurofibromatosis Authors: John A. Bachman, Benjamin M. Gyori --- INDRA Lab Team: Diana Kolusheva, Patrick A. Greene, Klas Karis, Albert Steppi, Peter K. Sorger Abstract: The scientific literature is growing exponentially, making it increasingly difficult for researchers to monitor new discoveries and identify the ones that have the potential to explain relevant questions in their research. To address this, we use text mining to read new scientific publications every day, update Neurofibromatosis-specific causal models and use those models to make connections, generate hypotheses, and highlight novelty. Our project consists of a platform, called EMMAA (emmaa.indra.bio), and two Neurofibromatosis causal models in the platform that together can help NF researchers capture knowledge and generate new therapeutic hypotheses. With the engagement of the NF community these resources have the potential to be a hub for the assembly of high-quality, actionable knowledge that is both human- and machine-readable. --- Introduction With the rapid growth of the scientific literature it is difficult for researchers to keep track of relevant discoveries, even in their own discipline. More difficult still is putting discoveries in context: does a new finding have an impact on therapeutic opportunities? Does it shed light on a previously obscure observation? Deriving this type of insight from the literature is particularly challenging in rare diseases such as neurofibromatosis (NF), where the community of researchers focused specifically on NF is small relative to the full body of literature with potential therapeutic relevance. It is therefore likely that novel therapeutic hypotheses could come from systematically connecting NF-specific data with causal knowledge about NF and cell biology more broadly. Our project consists of a platform, called the Ecosystem of Machine-Main

datasets.name: Targeting endothelial cell to macrophage communication in NF1 tumors
datasets.description_clean: Targeting endothelial cell to macrophage communication in NF1 tumors Targeting endothelial cell to macrophage communication in NF1 tumors CTF - Drug Discovery Initiative Registered Reports Principal Investigator: Brian Stansfield Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Brian Stansfield Institution: Augusta University Project Description: We will use three established animal models of angiogenesis and tumor growth to assess the efficacy of imipramine in suppressing pathologic angiogenesis and tumor growth. For all three models, littermate lysmCre+ and lysmCre- Nf1 flox/flox mice will be randomized 1:1 to vehicle or imipramine (7mg/kg/day). In the oxygen-induced retinopathy model, P7 pups will be subjected to 70% oxygen for 5 days and returned to normoxia for 5 days. Retinal flat mounts, single cell suspensions, and lysates will be used to assess avascular and neovascular area and quantify macrophage and endothelial cell content. In the hind limb ischemia model, 8-10 week old male and female littermates will undergo right femoral artery ligation and serial doppler ultrasound to assess collateralization over time. We will also employ micro-CT to quantify capillary density in both limbs. In the orthotropic tumor model, AT3 mouse breast tumor cells will be injected into mammary pads of 8 week old female littermates and tumor growth will be monitored using bioluminescent imaging and immunohistology. Innovation: This application is innovative on many levels: 1. First use of a novel macropinocytosis in translational animal models 2. Targeting intercellular communication to suppress angiogenesis and tumor growth 3. Seeks efficacy data in more than one tumor-relevant model Impact: If our hypothesis is correct and imipramine suppresses pathologic angiogenesis and tumor formation, we will be able to quickly move imipramine into Phase I/II human clinical trials for neurofibromas and MPNST as well as other NF1 manifestations for which macrophages are critical to disease pathogenesis. datasets.description_clean: Vision Restoration in Neurofibromatosis - Donor RGC Response to Microenvironment Vision Restoration in Neurofibromatosis - Donor RGC Response to Microenvironment GFF - Vision Restoration Initiative Principal Investigator: Petr Baranov Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Petr Baranov Institution: Schepens Eye Research Institute Project Description: In this proposal we aim to study the interaction of donor retinal neurons with host microenvironment in the mouse model of neurofibromatosis. Type 1 neurofibromatosis is an autosomal dominant, monogenic disorder that affects approximately 1 in every 3,000 individuals throughout the world. Optic pathway glioma (OPG) is the most frequent central nervous system tumor in children with NF1, affecting approximately 15–20% of patients. These tumors cause irreversible damage to retinal ganglion cells (RGCs), resulting in the vision loss. Recent progress by Gilbert Family Initiative investigators allowed to create several enabling animal models of NF1 OPG, which allowed to pinpoint the cellular and microenvironment features responsible for tumor formation and development. It also opened the possibility to explore vision restoration approaches in the neurofibromatosis microenvironment. datasets.description_clean: Phase 1.5 clinical trial of PRG-N-01 and data collection by MRI in NF2 patients Phase 1.5 clinical trial of PRG-N-01 and data collection by MRI in NF2 patients CTF - Contract Award Principal Investigator: Bum-Joon Park Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Bum-Joon Park, minyeoung Jae Institution: TBD Project Description: Neurofibromatosis type 2 (NF2) is a rare genetic disease for which no cure has been developed yet, and surgery is the only treatment method so far. It usually causes hearing loss, cerebellar dysfunction, glaucoma, optic nerve damage, seizures, loss of balance, numbness, or weakness in the arms and legs. The tumors are very close to the auditory and optic nerves. So, hearing loss and vision loss even could be brought on if surgery is not perfect. Therefore, there is an urgent need for a drug developed based on the cause of the disease. Monitoring the tumor formation site and size for efficacy verification is an important point as clinical data. Through this clinical research award, it is thought that it will be helpful to efficiently manage the clinical trial operation of new treatment and MRI data analysis. NF Data Curator App

datasets.name: Disrupting FBXW11-mediated degradation of NF1 to rescue haploinsufficiency
datasets.description_clean: Disrupting FBXW11-mediated degradation of NF1 to rescue haploinsufficiency Disrupting FBXW11-mediated degradation of NF1 to rescue haploinsufficiency GFF - Gene Therapy Initiative Principal Investigator: D. Wade Clapp Project Lead / Data Coordinator: D. Wade Clapp Institution: Indiana University Project Description: Learning disabilities and behavioral disorders such as attention deficit disorder occur in up to 70% of children with neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1). These behaviors are caused by mutation in one of the two copies of the NF1 gene that consequently lead to reduced levels of the NF1 gene product, neurofibromin. Studies in NF1 mouse models have revealed that these animals develop learning and behavioral problems similar to human patients and thus provide a valuable resource to study the disease and develop new and improved treatment strategies. In this project, we propose a new and innovative approach to treating learning and behavioral deficits in NF1 by boosting levels of the neurofibromin protein within the brain. We have discovered a new and important mechanism by which neurofibromin is regulated within the cell by interacting with another protein that marks neurofibromin for degradation. Further, we have shown that genetic disruption of that gene can restore neurofibromin protein levels within key brain areas that are responsible for the development of learning and behavioral disorders associated with NF1. A primary goal of this project is to better understand the signaling pathways that trigger neurofibromin for its degradation. If these studies are successful, they will provide the necessary justification to advance new gene and drug-based therapies to clinical trials for the treatment of learning disabilities and behavioral disorders in NF1. datasets.name: Gene therapy to prevent NF2-associated vestibular schwannomas
datasets.description_clean: Gene therapy to prevent NF2-associated vestibular schwannomas Gene therapy to prevent NF2-associated vestibular schwannomas CTF - Young Investigator Award Principal Investigator: Alexandra O'Donohue Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Alexandra O'Donohue Institution: University of Sydney Project Description: NF2-related schwannomatosis is a complex genetic disorder that features life-impacting and often painful schwannomas – including unilateral and bilateral vestibular schwannomas that affect balance and hearing. Current management of NF2-associated vestibular schwannoma involves careful monitoring and stereotactic radiosurgery to slow growth and/or microsurgical tumor removal. There are no current methods for preventing vestibular schwannomas, however gene therapy offers the potential to correct gene mutations before these tumors arise. NF2-related schwannomatosis is a challenging condition to create gene therapy cures for, however CRISPR-base editing (BE) strategies could precision correct point mutations in the NF2 gene at high efficiency – which make up to 40% of the mutation burden for NF2. The objective of this project is to employ CRISPR BE and AAV vector technologies to produce gene therapy vectors able to prevent or reduce the tumor burden associated with vestibular schwannoma. This study seeks to provide proof of principle data repairing human cells and genetically modified mice possessing the patient NF2 c.169C>T mutation. Aim 1 is to characterize our current strategy reaffirming high efficiency base-editing for NF2 c.169C>T in vitro and limited off target effects. A split CRISPR-ABE system will also be validated in vitro, verifying recombination of SpCas9 and preparing for future dual-AAV studies. Aim 2 is to develop targeting Schwann-cells vectors. Novel rAAVs that target Schwann cells (hSC2Pep1, hSC2Pep2) will be tested in Ai9 reporter mice using constitutive and Schwann-cell specific promoters. datasets.name: Exon skipping to treat Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (NF1) mutations
datasets.description_clean: Exon skipping to treat Neurofibromatosis Type 1 (NF1) mutations Administrative Principal Investigator: Deeann Wallis, PhD (University of Alabama, Birmingham) Principal Investigators: Deeann Wallis, PhD (University of Alabama, Birmingham); Linda Popplewell, PhD (Royal Holloway University of London) Lay Abstract Most currently available drugs to treat Neurofibromatosis Type I (NF1) are targeted at tumors; and as with many chemotherapies, they tend to have toxic side effects. Newer, less toxic therapies are needed. Antisense directed gene therapy, and more specifically exon skipping, is a successful therapeutic strategy for other diseases including Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD) which also affects children. Antisense directed gene therapy causes cells to “skip” over faulty pieces of the genetic code, leading to a truncated but still functional protein despite the genetic mutation. Antisense oligonucleotides (AONs) are short synthetic modified nucleic acids that bind RNA through base pairing and enable modulation of its expression. The project hypothesizes that antisense directed gene therapy can be utilized to treat NF1 and is designed to test that possibility. Exons, the coding part of genes, within the NF1 transcript that may be skipped and still maintain gene function must be identified. The first aim is to create copies of the NF1 gene that are missing these prioritized exons and test their function in cell-based molecular assays. This will involve computer-aided sequence analysis of the NF1 genomic region and the design of NF1 antisense phosphonodiamidite morpholino oligomers (PMOs) that target specific exons. datasets.name: Stimulation of retinal ganglion cells from Muller glia to restore vision
datasets.description_clean: Stimulation of retinal ganglion cells from Muller glia to restore vision Stimulation of retinal ganglion cells from Muller glia to restore vision GFF - Vision Restoration Initiative Principal Investigator: Tom Reh Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Tom Reh Institution: University of Washington Project Description: The retinal ganglion cells that relay information from the eye to the brain are often destroyed by gliomas in the optic nerve. Once these cells degenerate, they are not naturally replaced in people. However, in other animals, like zebrafish, the ganglion cells are replaced after injury by a support cell within the retina called a Müller glia cell. In the past 10 years we have developed methods to stimulate the retina to repair itself by coaxing the Müller glia in adult mice to behave like those in the fish. By over-expressing a key gene regulator, called Ascl1, in mature mouse Müller glia, we initiate a process that allows the mouse to regenerate new retinal neurons. This previous work, along with the considerable evidence that teleost fish can regenerate retinal neurons from Müller glia-derived retinal progenitors, was the basis for the “endogenous regeneration” subgroup’s plan to find a way to stimulate new ganglion cells in adult mice to treat the ganglion cell loss from optic nerve gliomas. In the past three years, we used a combination of approaches to discover additional factors that could (1) increase the efficiency of neural production from adult mouse Müller glia and (2) specifically direct the Müller glia to regenerate new ganglion cells. These two different factor combinations can regenerate new neurons that resemble several different types of ganglion cells, at a very high efficiency; however, they do not fully mature, or send axons to the optic nerve. Therefore, in this proposal, we outline experiments to further improve the regeneration of ganglion cells from Muller glia. NF Data Curator App

datasets.description_clean: Identifying markers of response and resistance to experimental therapies for neurofibromas Identifying markers of response and resistance to experimental therapies for neurofibromas NTAP - Open Proposal Program Principal Investigator: Michael Fisher Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Michael Fisher Institution: Children's Hospital of Philadelphia Project Description: This project establishes a standardized biorepository using samples from two completed CDMRP NF Clinical Trials Consortium (NFCTC) studies (NF108: Phase II Study of Binimetinib in Children and Adults With NF1 Plexiform Neurofibromas and NF105: Cabozantinib for Plexiform Neurofibromas in Subjects With NF1 in Children and Adults). The repository is built to support future research on tumor biomarkers as related to neurofibromas, their response to various treatments and pharmacodynamic dosing. As the preliminary effort, the initiative: (a) assessed the feasibility of sample collection, transfer from the study sites, and storage at the Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia Biorepository Resource Center; (b) developed governance policies for sample use and sharing; and (c) ensures compliance with all human tissue and data regulations. The efforts have created an inventory of 106 blood samples and 2 tumor samples donated by pediatric and adult participants in NF108 and pediatric participants in NF105. When the data from the parent clinical trials is published, mechanisms to enable interested parties to request these samples will be launched. Future directions include expansion of these efforts to include additional samples from additional NFCTC clinical trials and linking of the samples to the clinical trial outcome data via the NFCTC Data Coordinating Center. datasets.name: RAFT-polymerized nanoparticles for delivery of NF1 cDNA to Schwann cells
datasets.description_clean: RAFT-polymerized nanoparticles for delivery of NF1 cDNA to Schwann cells GFF - Gene Therapy Initiative Principal Investigator: Cherry Gupta Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Cherry Gupta Institution: Battelle Memorial Institute Project Description: Neurofibromatosis 1 is caused due to genetic mutations in the NF1 gene which results in the loss of function of the neurofibromin protein. Neurofibromin is a tumor suppressor whose disfunction leads to the development of benign and malignant tumors in the nervous system (NS). Reconstituting functional neurofibromin by delivering the correct version of the gene to cells in the NS presents a promising treatment that has high potential for clinical translation. However, this has been challenging due to (1) the difficulty of encapsulating and delivering the large NF1 gene, which is out of reach of viral vectors since they have a small cargo capacity, and (2) the lack of safe targeting strategies that can preferentially deliver therapeutics to cells in the nervous system. To overcome these challenges, our team from Battelle and the University of Alabama proposes to use synthetic polymer nanoparticles (PNP) to encapsulate and deliver the NF1 gene to cells in the nervous system. A high-throughput design, synthesis and screening platform developed by Battelle will enable screening of a diverse library of PNPs to identify the most suitable vectors which can efficiently encapsulate and deliver the NF1 gene to cultured immortalized human nerve cells (in vitro) and in an NF1 specific mouse disease model (in vivo). Data obtained from the screening assays will be used to identify candidates most likely to succeed at targeting and delivering the NF1 gene to the PNS. This approach, to simultaneously test a large variety of delivery candidates at an early stage, both in vitro and in vivo, will help us avoid the pitfalls of conventional drug development cycles and identify delivery vector candidates with high promise for clinical success. datasets.name: Repurposing anti-retroviral drugs to treat NF2 related tumours
datasets.description_clean: Repurposing anti-retroviral drugs to treat NF2 related tumours Repurposing anti-retroviral drugs to treat NF2 related tumours CTF - Contract Award Principal Investigator: Clemens Hanemann Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Clemens Hanemann, C Oliver Hanemann Institution: University of Plymouth Project Description: NF2 related schwannomatosis (formerly Neurofibromatosis type 2) is caused by loss of the tumor suppressor protein called Merlin (that suppresses tumor development). Loss of Merlin causes a genetic predisposition to schwannoma, meningioma and ependymoma tumors. These tumors may occur spontaneously, but symptoms occur earlier and are more severe in those with the inherited condition. These tumors may cause, depending on location, a variety of symptoms. Some patients have a huge tumor load leading to life threatening complications. Surgical management and radiotherapy are the mainstay of treatment but potentially carry long term morbidity (side effects) and are not always possible. Effective and safe drug treatments are urgently needed. We have discovered a new potential therapeutic target called Human Endogenous Retrovirus Type K (HERVK). HERVK is a virus belonging to larger group called Endogenous Retroviruses (ERVs) that have evolved to be part of the human genome. Normally HERVK is inactive, but its reactivation has been observed in some cancers. Our recent research has shown higher levels of HERVK in both schwannoma and meningioma caused by loss of Merlin. Importantly HERVK proteins contribute to schwannoma and meningioma development and growth. Two medications that are usually used to treat HIV, called Ritonavir and Lopinavir, decrease the levels of HERVK and HERVK related molecules promoting tumor growth and survival. This reduced growth and survival of patients’ schwannoma and meningioma tumor cells in the laboratory (in vitro). Ritonavir and Lopinavir have been used for many years to treat HIV patients and have a greater effect when used in combination

datasets.name: Genome Editing with Engineered Vectors to Correct Neurofibromatosis Type I
datasets.description_clean: Genome Editing with Engineered Vectors to Correct Neurofibromatosis Type I GTI Phase A Project Administrative Principal Investigator: Charles Gersbach, PhD (Duke University) Principal Investigators: Charles Gersbach, PhD (Duke University); David V. Schaffer, PhD (University of California, Berkeley); David G. Kirsch, MD, PhD (Duke University) Lay Abstract Neurofibromatosis type I (NF1) is caused by mutations to the NF1 gene that lead to the development of tumors of the peripheral nervous system. Gene therapy has seen tremendous advances in recent years in the delivery of genes to select tissues to compensate for mutations that cause genetic disease. However, there are two primary challenges that prevent extending these developments to NF1. First, there is currently no method to deliver genes to the cells that initiate tumor development. Second, the NF1 gene is particularly large and is not accommodated within the size-restricted viruses currently used for gene therapy. A team was assembled with the unique and complementary expertise to overcome both of these challenges and apply the resulting technology to clinically relevant animal models of NF1. First, an innovative strategy will be used to engineer new viruses that target the tumor initiating cells of the peripheral nervous system. Second, CRISPR-based genome editing will be used to restore the mutated NF1 gene, thereby circumventing the need to deliver a copy of the full-length NF1 gene sequence. Finally, the ability of these engineered viruses and genome editing strategies to reduce tumor burden in a mouse model of NF1 will be tested. Each of these approaches have been successfully applied in the context of other disease areas, and through this project this success will be extended to address the challenges of developing a gene therapy for NF1. This work will also involve several technological advances that will be generally useful to the field and complement other strategies being explored to apply gene therapy

datasets.name: Developing a thrombopoietin inhibitor to treat NF2 hearing loss and schwannoma growth
datasets.description_clean: Developing a thrombopoietin inhibitor to treat NF2 hearing loss and schwannoma growth Developing a thrombopoietin inhibitor to treat NF2 hearing loss and schwannoma growth CTF - Drug Discovery Initiative Registered Reports Principal Investigator: Lawrence Sherman Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Lawrence Sherman, Lei Xu Institution: Oregon Health and Science University Project Description: Patients with neurofibromatosis 2 (NF2) often suffer hearing loss, balance problems, and facial paralysis linked to the growth of tumors, called schwannomas, on their acoustic nerves. We previously found that a drug called losartan could prevent hearing loss in a mouse model of NF2. Although losartan is generally safe, it is unclear if it will be effective in NF2 patients and sometimes has side effects that may not be well tolerated by NF2 patients. One of the ways that losartan works is by affecting cells called platelets which can contribute to inflammation around tumors and affect the cellular machinery needed for hearing. Here, we plan to use a different drug, called a thrombopoietin antisense oligonucleotide (TPO-ASO), that is being tested in clinical trials for other diseases and which also regulates platelets but does not have other effects linked to losartan. This study will help define how losartan functions to preserve hearing in the presence of acoustic nerve schwannomas, and test if TPO-ASO could be a drug candidate to protect or improve hearing and reduce tumor growth in NF2 patients. Selumetinib is the only FDA-approved targeted therapy for pediatric PN. Repositioning other FDA-approved drugs to treat PN can significantly speed up the research process and clinical evaluation. The relatively apparent safety and dosage information about FDA-approved drugs can substantially reduce the risks and increase the success rate in new clinical trials for PN. We developed a data analysis pipeline to prioritize the drug candidates from PN cell line-based drug screening data by computational analysis and NIH database searches. The cysteinyl leukotriene receptor antagonists, including Montelukast, Zafirlukast, and Pranlukast, are among the top candidates that have inhibitory effects on PN cells. datasets.description_clean: Nanoparticle Delivery of Therapeutic NF1 Signaling ERPs to Schwann Cells Nanoparticle Delivery of Therapeutic NF1 Signaling ERPs to Schwann Cells GFF - Gene Therapy Initiative Principal Investigator: Kenneth Sims Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Kenneth Sims Institution: Battelle Memorial Institute Project Description: Recent advances in genome editing provide an opportunity to therapeutically address loss of the tumor suppressor gene neurofibromin 1 (NF1) and prevent neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1). However, two key challenges remain to translate a NF1 gene therapy to the clinic: 1) development of a broadly applicable therapeutic approach for all individuals with NF1 rather than mutation-specific approaches, and 2) the ability to load and deliver large payloads (>4.7 kb) to specific cell types, such as Schwann cells. A new, multidisciplinary collaboration between Battelle Memorial Institute and the University of California Davis seeks to overcome these challenges. We will use gene editing to regulate the Ras-MAPK pathway in a similar manner to a currently available broadly applicable therapeutic approach that uses an FDA-approved small molecule drug. Our treatment is intended to require one or a few administered doses instead of the twice-daily drug regimen currently available. The overall goal of this project is to create targeted epigenetic regulatory proteins (ERPs) to be transient therapeutic payloads that cause persistent down-regulation of mitogen-activated protein kinases 1 and 2 (MEK1/2) and to deliver plasmid DNA (pDNA) encoding these ERPs to Schwann cells (SCs) in both human and mouse models. This study will: Create ERPs to induce long-term pathway repression, Identify, synthesize, and screen polymer nanoparticles (PNPs) to find candidate(s) that deliver ERP payloads and restrict activity to Schwann cells. Research in Hippo pathway signaling and its role in driving tumor development has increased greatly in the last few years and the significance of this pathway has driven the development of new small molecule inhibitors to target this important signalling pathway. datasets.name: Early treatment of cutaneous neurofibromas type 1 (cNF) to markedly improve patient's quality of life
datasets.description_clean: Early treatment of cutaneous neurofibromas type 1 (cNF) to markedly improve patient's quality of life Early treatment of cutaneous neurofibromas type 1 (cNF) to markedly improve patient's quality of life NTAP - DHART SPORE Developmental Research Program Principal Investigator: Thomas E. Milner Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Wangcun Jia Institution: University of California, Irvine Project Description: The most common complication for neurofibromatosis 1 (NF1) patients is the appearance of cutaneous neurofibromas (cNF), which is considered as the most significant life burden of NF1. Current management of the tumors is eradication often with significant morbidity. The goals of project are to improve the quality of life of NF1 patients through the identification of a biomarker to locate and evaluate cNF and through the development of a laser therapy solution. The proposed research has two aims. Aim 1 is to demonstrate an optical biomarker and validate using histology, and Aim 2 is to identify and demonstrate laser treatment mechanism of action. In Aim 1, two optical imaging modalities are utilized, Spatial Frequency Domain Imaging (SFDI) and optical coherence tomography (OCT) to first detect and then image tissue microstructure of cNF tumors. In Aim 2, two laser treatment modalities will be tested. The first treatment approach utilizes laser light to target the tumor vasculature to induce local hyperthermia and eradicate the tumor. The second treatment alternative utilizes near-infrared laser radiation to spatially target water and collagen to induce local hyperthermia and eradicate the tumor. Approved Intended Data Use Statements NF Data Curator App

MPNSTs are aggressive, difficult to treat, and are often detected only when they are already advanced. One of the biggest challenges for patients and doctors is that we currently have no reliable way to predict which pNFs will become dangerous or to detect malignant transformation early enough for effective treatment. Recent research in many cancers has shown that changes in the way tumor cells use and store fats—also called lipids—play an important role in tumor growth and survival. Lipids are building blocks for cell membranes, store energy, and can also act as signals that influence how tumors behave. datasets.name: A syndrome-level composite resistance index to inform the use of empiric antibiotic therapies
datasets.description_clean: A syndrome-level composite resistance index to inform the use of empiric antibiotic therapies Summary Antibiotics are most often prescribed empirically to treat infection syndromes before the causative bacteria and their susceptibility to antibiotics are confirmed . The effectiveness of antibiotic therapies is compromised by the emergence and spread of antibiotic-resistant bacteria . Hence guidelines on empiric antibiotic therapy are a key component of current clinical care for infection syndromes and must be informed by knowledge of bacterial resistance. In this work, we used the ATLAS dataset to derive a composite index of antibiotic resistance for common infection syndromes. We argue that this could be a more clinically relevant measure of resistance, as opposed to reporting resistance rates for individual pathogens, to inform on the appropriateness of empiric antibiotic therapies. We developed a framework that integrated data on antibiotic prescribing guidelines, aetiology of infections, access to and cost of antibiotics, with antibiotic susceptibility from global antimicrobial resistance (AMR) surveillance datasets to derive this index. The results are presented in an interactive web app to allow users to visualise underlying resistance rates to first-line empiric antibiotics for their infection syndromes and countries of interest. We conclude that the ATLAS dataset, in its current form, is not suitable to inform empiric antibiotic therapies for many syndromes but that a framework like ours will be useful going forward with increasing coverage and improved sampling of antibiotic resistance surveillance. Wade Clapp, Jaishri Blakeley, Brigitte Widemann, Lu Le Institution: Indiana University; Johns Hopkins University; National Institutes of Health; University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center Project Description: Plexiform neurofibromas (PNs) PNs are complex nerve and soft tissue tumors that affect 25-50% of people with NF1, cause serious lifelong morbidity and mortality due to organ compression, and progress to malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumors (MPNST) in ~8-13% of patients. datasets.description_clean: A multidimensional approach to understanding and treating sleep disorders in children and adolescents with neurofibromatosis Type 1 A multidimensional approach to understanding and treating sleep disorders in children and adolescents with neurofibromatosis Type 1 NTAP - Francis S. Collins Scholars Program Principal Investigator: Natalie Pride Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Natalie Pride Institution: Royal North Shore Hospital Project Description: Research highlights the role of the NF1 gene in regulating the sleep-wake cycle, with NF1 heterozygosity associated with an abnormal sleep phenotype and circadian rhythm in Drosophila. Despite these findings, there remains limited knowledge about sleep in NF1. This research plan addresses critical gaps through a four-phase approach. Phase-1, is underway and funded, revealing preliminary data from actigraphy and sleep assessments indicating that children with NF1 exhibit poorer sleep efficiency, longer sleep onset, and poorer sleep hygiene. Additionally, a sevenfold increase in children with NF1 surpassing screening criteria for periodic limb movement disorder (PLMD) and sleepdisordered breathing (SDB) was identified, along with a high risk for insomnia. CTF - Young Investigator Award Principal Investigator: Charlene Iltis Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Charlene Iltis Institution: Sloan-Kettering Institute for Cancer Research Project Description: Neurofibromatosis type 1 is a genetic disease affecting more than one in three thousand births worldwide, making it the most common genetic disease. The disease affects different cells and is therefore defined by a myriad of symptoms ranging from benign tumors to malignancy. At the molecular level, neurofibromatosis type 1 is characterized by the defect of a component regulating a pathway that is originally a cell proliferation pathway called the Ras-Erk signaling pathway. Indeed, the modification of one of the components of this signaling pathway called Neurofibromin is at the origin of this pathology. As a result of this modification, the cells proliferate at a very high level and form benign tumors such as the neurofibroma plexiform. This benign tumor is formed because of the NF1 gene mutation and its evolution to a malignant tumor called Malignant Peripheral Nerve Sheath Tumor (MPNST) is made possible by the further addition of mutations. Significant effort and resources have been expended to develop agents that block this cascade to reverse tumor growth. Unfortunately, this strategy has proven ineffective in controlling the growth of malignant lesions such as MPNST, which have additional mutations. In 10% of cases, plexiform neurofibromas show nuclear and cellular abnormalities that accompany progression towards malignancy. Once they transform into MPNSTs, therapeutic options become severely limited. While mutations in various genes like CDKN2A, TP53, SUZ12, and EED may indicate completed transformation to MPNST, there are few early genetic indicators that characterize transition from PN to MPNST. Additionally, cis-regulation of expression in genes of interest have been studied in PN and MPNSTs extensively, but little is known about the trans-regulation of gene expression via microRNAs in these tumors. Preliminary gene expression analysis of publicly available PNs and MPNST data and previous research has identified genes that have greater expression in MPNSTs than PNs. Many of these genes are also subject to trans-regulation of expression by one or more microRNAs. One possibility is that the reduced repression of these target genes by mutated miRNAs lead to the observed expression changes. Moreover, since miRNAs have strict sequence prerequisites for viability, they may accumulate and manifest early mutations from evolving genomic instability in abnormally growing cells of PNs. We hypothesize that miRNA genes mutated due to early genomic instability accompanying malignant transformation of PNs to MPNSTs act as early indicators of this transformation. The goal of this proposal is to identify genomic variants in miRNA genes and their critical domains that are key differentiators between MPNSTs and PNs. We propose to use recently published miRNA-specific variant calling methods and supervised machine learning approach

datasets.name: Interdisciplinary Approaches to Cancer Metastasis
datasets.description_clean: Metastasis remains the principal cause of mortality among cancer patients. For a tumor cell to metastasize, it must escape the primary tumor, successfully negotiate various molecular and cellular interactions, and colonize a new microenvironment to establish a secondary tumor. To predict how and when cancer will metastasize and to develop more effective treatments, a better understanding is needed about how these individual events - tumor growth, dissemination, colonization, and survival - contribute to the complex metastatic process. Recent advances in live-cell imaging, characterization of circulating tumor cells, experimental models of tumor dormancy, descriptions of tumor cell – immune system crosstalk, cell and tissue mechanics, and single-cell genomic and proteomic analysis have provided quantitative data that can be used to build testable mathematical and computational models of tumor metastasis.   The Interdisciplinary Approaches to Cancer Metastasis workshop, to be held June 12-14, 2017, in Seattle, WA at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center, will bring together ~25 early stage investigators (within 15 years of terminal degree) across four NCI-supported programs, the Innovative Molecular Analysis Technologies (IMAT) program, the Informatics Technology for Cancer Research (ITCR) program, the Cancer Systems Biology Consortium (CSBC) and the Physical Sciences-Oncology Network (PS-ON), along with select outside investigators to tackle important questions in cancer metastasis. The goal is to form teams that utilize the technologies and computational approaches championed by IMAT and ITCR along with the cancer systems biology and physical oncology viewpoints employed within the CSBC and PS-ON. datasets.name: Introduction to R
datasets.description_clean: Introduction In this session, we covered the basics of using R - including installation of R and RStudio and working with an interactive tutorial called Swirl. Installing R This depends on your operating system - head over to The Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) to download. Installing RStudio I highly recommend learning to use R within RStudio; it provides a number of features that assist beginner (and advanced!) programmers. To download, visit RStudio. There are a number of cool features! Learn about how you can use RStudio effectively here. For example, some of the things we covered were: 1. After typing code into a script, you can move the cursor to that line and press Ctrl+Enter (or Cmd+Enter on a Mac) to execute that line; this avoids copying and pasting each line into the console! 2. Save early and save often! We learned how to open a new R Script and save it - remember to use the .R file extension. 3. I highly recommend typing all code into a script, and add comments (line that begins with the ) as you go. Once you figure out something, you'll want to remember how you did it! Learning R interactively with Swirl We started using a teaching tool called Swirl - you can read more about it here. You can follow the instructions here for getting it installed and running. The basic steps were install R and RStudio, and then in the RStudio console type: install.packages("swirl") To load swirl (or any other package you may want to use in R), you type (in the RStudio console): library("swirl") Then, just follow the instructions! There are a number of other courses available besides the basic R introduction that we began working through. You can see these at the course repository. For example, to install the course on Exploratory Data Analysis, in the RStudio console you can type the following (you might have already typed some of these things!): library(swirl) installfromswirl("ExploratoryDataAnalysis") swirl() And the course should be available in your menu!

datasets.name: Development and Validation of PRO Measures to Assess Pain in Individuals with NF1 and pNF
datasets.description_clean: NTAP project The Development and Validation of PRO Measures to Assess Pain in Individuals with NF1 and pNF Initiative: PRO   Name: Pamela Wolters Contact Email: woltersp@mail.nih.gov Name: Schorry (Wolters) Contact Email: elizabeth.schorry@cchmc.org Name: Tonsgard (Wolters) Contact Email: jtonsgar@peds.bsd.uchicago.edu Name: Walsh (Wolters) Contact Email: kwalsh@childrensnational.org Dates: 1-23-14 to 2-28-18 Tumor Focus: plexiform neurofibroma Application: Clinical Endpoint Tool   Background: Clinical trials for the treatment of PNs in children and adults with NF1 are underway. The FDA recommends including endpoints in NF1 clinical trials that assess changes in symptoms, such as pain, in addition to tumor reduction. Currently, no valid PRO measures exist that assess PN-related pain and its effect on daily functioning. The first phase of this limited-site study is to modify existing PRO pain tools using qualitative methods to ensure understanding of the concepts being assessed and to examine how the current tools work in the NF1/PN population. The second phase is to examine the psychometric properties of the modified PROs in individuals with NF1 and PNs.   Goals of Project: To produce the most reliable, valid, and feasible measures of pain intensity and pain interference, as end-points in clinical trials or intervention studies.   Aims: PHASE 1: QUALITATIVE RESEARCH: Primary objective: To evaluate existing pain measures for use as endpoints in clinical trials for individuals with NF1 and PNs using qualitative feedback from patients with NF1, PNs, and pain [Pain intensity: Numeric Rating Scale (NRS-11); Pain interference: Pain Interference Index (PII)], Secondary Objective: To convert the measures (including changes) into an electronic format.   PHASE 2: QUANTITATIVE RESEARCH: Primary objective: To evaluate the final modified versions of the NRS-11 and PII on reliability, validity, sensitivity to change, and feasibility in individuals with NF

datasets.name: Optimizing strategies to improve visual recovery from NF1 optic glioma
datasets.description_clean: Optimizing strategies to improve visual recovery from NF1 optic glioma VRI Subgroup: Neuroprotection/Neuroenhancement Principal Investigator: David Gutmann, MD, PhD (Washington University in St. Louis) Personnel: Jason Papke, MS (Staff Scientist) Suzanne Scheaffer (Staff Scientist) Caroline Tang, MD, PhD (Postdoctoral Fellow) Lay Abstract Children with Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) are prone to the development of benign brain tumors that affect the optic pathway (optic gliomas) and result in vision loss. While current chemotherapy is effective at halting tumor growth, few patients regain vision. For this reason, it is imperative to identify new treatments that prevent or restore vision loss from these tumors. Research over the past 15 years in the Gutmann laboratory has demonstrated that mice engineered with Nf1 gene mutations develop optic gliomas and tumor associated vision loss. In the current GVRI proposal, we plan to use a novel discovery strategy to identify a core molecular signature of vision recovery following treatment in mice, and employ these findings to evaluate promising candidates in preclinical studies in genetically engineered mice with optic gliomas and vision loss. Leveraging the GVRI team science paradigm, discoveries made using these mice will be validated in other experimental paradigms developed in the Reh, Zack, and Young laboratories. In addition, novel findings emanating from other team efforts will be evaluated in these Nf1 optic glioma mice. Taken together, we aim to identify targeted therapeutic strategies that prevent or ameliorate vision loss in children with NF1 associated optic pathway gliomas. This study focuses on a specific group of patients with NF2: adolescents and young adults (AYA) who develop meningiomas, which are tumors that grow on the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. Patients with NF2 are usually diagnosed at around 20 years of age, at which point half of them present with multiple meningiomas. We now recognize that brain tumors in AYA patients and adult patients behave differently, which is thought to relate to differences in their biology. While these tumors are not malignant, they can cause pain, itching, and disfigurement, resulting in significant socio-emotional repercussions of patients living with NF1. Furthermore, in some cases pNFs can transform into a type of cancer known as malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumors (MPNSTs). To date, the only approved therapy for NF1 is the drug selumetininb, which is limited for treating a subset of patients with plexiform neurofibromas. One of the main challenges to identify effective therapies for NF1 is the high complexity of these tumors. They contain a wide variety of cell types and present abundant extracellular proteins, making very challenging to replicate their behavior in laboratory models. To study them, we have successfully created patient-derived organoid models. These are miniature 3D replicas of tumors grown in the lab derived from tumor tissues surgically removed during patients’ standard of care procedures. These organoids closely mirror the characteristics of the original tumors, allowing us to study NF1 more accurately. While these tumors are not malignant, they can cause pain, itching, and disfigurement, resulting in significant socio-emotional repercussions of patients living with NF1. To date, the only approved therapy for NF1 is the drug selumetininb, which is limited for treating a subset of patients with plexiform neurofibromas. One of the main challenges to identify effective therapies for NF1 is the high complexity of these tumors. They contain a wide variety of cell types and present abundant extracellular proteins, making very challenging to replicate their behavior in laboratory models. To study them, we have successfully created patient-derived organoid models. These are miniature 3D replicas of tumors grown in the lab derived from tumor tissues surgically removed during patients’ standard of care procedures. These organoids closely mirror the characteristics of the original tumors, allowing us to study NF1 more accurately. These problems include weak muscles, difficulty with movements, feeling tired easily, and not feeling confident in physical activities. Studies have shown that these muscle issues affect many children with NF1. In 2021, our research team conducted a small study to see if a supplement called L-carnitine could help with these muscle problems in NF1. The study showed that L-carnitine was safe and seemed to work, but we need to do a bigger study to be sure. The new study will have two groups: one will take L-carnitine and the other will take a placebo. The children will switch between the two groups during the study. The amount of L-carnitine they take will be based on their weight. This larger study will give us more information about how L-carnitine affects muscles in NF1. It will also help doctors make better decisions about how to treat NF1 based on scientific evidence. NF Data Curator App

Collins Scholars Program Principal Investigator: Harish Vasudevan Project Lead / Data Coordinator: Harish Vasudevan Institution: UCSF Project Description: Neural crest derived Schwann cells give rise to neurofibromas, schwannomas, and MPNSTs. Despite their shared embryonic origin, the clinical course of these tumors is quite different. Neurofibromas and schwannomas are benign lesions that are well managed with local therapy while MPNSTs are aggressive tumors that metastasize and have poor outcomes.1 MPNSTs can arise from neurofibromas or schwannomas following malignant transformation in the setting of NF1 loss or ionizing radiation.2–5 NF1 encodes a tumor suppressor that inhibits Ras signaling, a conserved pathway required for development and misactivated in 1/3 of cancers6 including Schwann cell derived tumors.7 However, only a minority of neurofibromas and schwannomas progress to MPNSTs, suggesting additional steps are required. In addition to NF1, MPNSTs harbor mutations in the Polycomb Repressive Complex 2 (PRC2),8–10 a chromatin modifier which regulates gene repression in development and cancer via H3K27 trimethylation.11 My objective is to elucidate how epigenetic mechanisms contribute to malignant transformation in Ras activated tumors.
